body.description: As a new member of the Tower series, the Tower 500 shares the same silhouette with its predecessors, offering full display to the system components. It provides excellent hardware expandability to accommodates latest PC hardware without compensating the building experience. The Tower 500 delivers superior thermal performance thanks to its air and water cooling compatibility and vertical interior design that utilizes air convection, keeping the motion high and the temperature low. reviews.reviewDate: Reviewed in the United States on November 4, 2023
reviews.reviewText: Awesome case, very well made and thought out, super easy to build in and you can fit a rtx 4090! For the cpu cooler I used an Arctic freeze 280, in order to fit the 280 cooler if you put a 140 fan at the top of the case you need to put it under the top cover on the outside of the main chamber to make room for the radiator and 140 fans.Everything looks and runs amazing, tons of airflow so zero problems with temps, if you are interested in this case trust me just buy it, not the cheapest case but it’s very high quality and thought out, even has built in cable holders in the back so you can route everything and make it look clean, also you don’t need any tools to take all the main panels off, no taking out little screws and all that, I got the green color and imo it looks great!

reviews.reviewDate: Reviewed in the United States on October 29, 2023
reviews.reviewTitle: 4.0 out of 5 stars Awesome case but with a few things to keep in mind
reviews.reviewText: This case is great, but there were a few minor issues that prevented me from utilizing the customization potential to the max...First of all, this technically does fix 360mm CPU cooling AIOs. However, they will *only* fit standing up against the side of the case. So you can either have fans facing outwards (towards the glass) and see the "ugly" radiator on the inside, or you can have the fans facing inside and have the radiator on the outside. I was hoping to have it on the top of the case so the fans pointed down so the RGB could illuminate the case. Instead, I have them facing against the glass side so that they illuminate the wall behind the case, which is quite nice.Another problem with this is that there are two USB header ports needed to plug in the USB ports on the front of the case... but my motherboard didn't have enough for all I needed. If you like having access to USBs on the front of your case, be sure to check motherboard specs and ensure you have enough headers to plug them in. The motherboard also had to go in "upside down" (but I'll blame ASUS for this one; ASUS x670e-a).The third issue I had involved the GPU. I bought a big chonker (AMD Ryzen 7 7800x3D 8-core) which fits just perfectly against the side of the case, but something to do with how it was plugged into the motherboard meant I wasn't able to fully utilize the GPU (there are two ports to plug it in, I initially had it plugged in furthest from the CPU; closest to the side of the case). I had to plug it in closer to the CPU which basically messed up the placement of other PC compartments in the case. I also had to remove a bottom inner panel to fit it in as it was barely (maybe 10-20mm) too long.Finally... one of the rubber feet fell off not 5 minutes after removing from packaging. Not much of an issue, but I tried reattaching it but it just kept falling off.I love how the top of the case has a panel that is easy to remove, but what I don't like is how difficult it is to remove the whole casing from the top. Especially if I have USB components plugged in. Remember to remove those before removing the top part of the case! The cable management is also pretty cool-looking and easy to figure out. There's a lot of space behind, above, and below the case to hide cables and manage in a way that's functional.All in all, I don't necessarily regret purchasing this case, but I am a little disappointed in how much compromise I had to make in order to get my PC to work properly. I bought this thinking I could have a lot of room for customization with how it looks, but honestly it feels somewhat too small for what I was expecting and thinking lol There was a lot of time spent on moving components around to ensure everything was getting adequate power and was positioned in such a way that it would fit and I could see the RGB and LCD screens properly (I have the NZXT Kraken Elite AIO which has the LCD screen). I'm confident that I can find other ways to improve how it looks but right now I'm fairly happy with it!

It's a beautiful thing !...and the metal is slightly thicker/sturdier than all the other cases I've ever owned. A slightly better gauge of metal was used I think. It's a modular as you can imagine and it all comes apart and goes back together easily. It is the most beautiful case I've ever owned.

Un gabinete bastante grande para ser dirijido a mini ITX sin duda este gabinete no tendrás problemas para acomodar cables o componentes grandes o que generan mucho calor aunq el precio es algo elevado se compensa que le puedes poner una fuente ATX que son más baratas, de igual forma el gabinete es compatible con tarjetas madre micro ATX aunq depende el diseño de la tarjeta madre puede que tengas que renunciar algunas conexiones sata, incluye 2 ventiladores de 140 mm y no lo menciona el manual pero incluye también 2 spliters de 2 entradas para conectar 2 ventiladores a una toma de ventilador en la tarjeta madre y los mismos ventiladores tienen un divisor para conectar otro ventilador, es fácil de desarmar ya que no nesecitas un desarmador para quitar la mayoría de los accesorios, recomiendo este gabinete si vas a colocar componentes grandes o que neseciten de una buena refrigeración ya que el tamaño da para eso, en caso de que no recomiendo su versión anterior el tower 100 que es más compacto.

reviews.reviewText: super case vraiment le fun a monter mais certainement un brin plus complexe a assembler qu'un case standard.
